Here are the MSTest patterns for each scenario (requires MSTest 3.9–3.10+):

**1. Windows-only (registry tests) — `[OSCondition]`**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[OSCondition(OperatingSystems.Windows)]
public void Registry_ReadsInstallPath()
{
    var value = Registry.GetValue(@"HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\MyApp", "InstallDir", null);
    Assert.IsNotNull(value);
}
```

**2. Skip in CI (local GPU required) — `[CICondition]`**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[CICondition(ConditionMode.Exclude)]
public void GpuRenderer_ProducesExpectedFrame()
{
    var frame = _renderer.RenderFrame();
    Assert.IsNotNull(frame);
}
```

**3. Flaky external API — `[Retry]`**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
[Retry(3)]
[Timeout(10000)]
public async Task WeatherApi_ReturnsForecast()
{
    var forecast = await _client.GetForecastAsync(_testContext.CancellationToken);
    Assert.IsNotNull(forecast);
}
```
Use `[Retry]` only for genuinely flaky external dependencies — not to mask race conditions or shared-state bugs.

**4. Temp file cleanup — `[TestCleanup]` / `IDisposable`**
```csharp
[TestClass]
public sealed class FileProcessorTests : IDisposable
{
    private readonly string _tempFile;

    public FileProcessorTests()
    {
        _tempFile = Path.GetTempFileName();
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public void Process_WritesExpectedOutput()
    {
        File.WriteAllText(_tempFile, "input");
        FileProcessor.Process(_tempFile);
        Assert.AreEqual("processed", File.ReadAllText(_tempFile));
    }

    // Runs even if the test fails
    public void Dispose()
    {
        if (File.Exists(_tempFile))
            File.Delete(_tempFile);
    }
}
```

You can also use `[TestCleanup]` instead of `IDisposable` — both run after every test, even on failure. The execution order is: `[TestCleanup]` → `DisposeAsync` → `Dispose`.
